%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Material hierarchy}
\label{sec:material_hierarchy}
%------------------------------

To analyze material conversion chains,
we employ a hierarchy for our analysis.
Our hierarchy is:
(a)~statepoint, a material stream that is an input or output of a process,
(b)~mixture, a combination of compounds and/or elements
that exist at a statepoint,
(c)~compound, and
(d)~element.
This ordering enables later incorporation of
components (a configuration of mixtures) and
products (an assembly of components)
between mixture and statepoint in our hierarchy.

With this approach,
the material at any statepoint
may be described as a mixture of compounds,
and the compounds an arrangement of elements.
For this paper, we adopt subscript symbols for the hierarchy
as shown in Table~\ref{tab:hierarchy_nomenclature}.
For example, $B_{m,k}$ gives the material exergy ($B$)
of a mixture (subscript $m$) at statepoint $k$.
Our choice of $j$ (for elements) and $i$ (for compounds)
follows \citet{Valero_2015}.

