%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The exergy of materials}
\label{sec:exergy_of_materials}
%------------------------------

Material exergy is the exergy of a mixture of compounds
that exist at a statepoint ($B_k$).
Material exergy is the maximum amount of work
that could be extracted
by a process that takes the mixture
to equilibrium with the reference environment,
defined by its temperature ($T_0$), pressure ($P_0$), and chemical composition.
Thus, the total exergy of a material ($B$)
is the sum of the work of four reversible processes
that bring the system
(a)~from $T$ and $P$ to
    $T_0$ and $P_0$
    (without changes in the chemical composition)
(b)~from its chemical composition
    to the reference chemical composition****ex****
    (while the system remains at $T_0$ and $P_0$)
(c)~from its concentration at the statepoint to pure **state**
(d)~from its dispersed state to cohesive state.
%processes a through d have exergy associated
%Ex. T and P, concentration, dispersion (mine), compound that changes

Natural resources have a positive material exergy ($b$ in kJ/mol)
because they have a chemical composition
different from their Environment.
Material exergy is comprised of four components:
physical exergy ($b_{ph}$),
chemical exergy ($b_{ch}$),
concentration exergy ($b_c$),
and comminution exergy ($b_{com}$).
Comminution exergy is minimal and ignored for a material conversion chain analysis
\citep[p.~280]{Valero_2015}.
Here, we assume that the material is at
$T_0$ and $P_0$;
thus, physical exergy ($b_{ph}$) is zero.

Reference environments can include the atmosphere,
the ocean, or the Earth's crust.
Species in reference environments are characterized
by partial pressure ($P_i = P_0 y_i$) in the atmosphere,
by concentrations ($C_i$) in the ocean,
and by mole fraction ($y_i$)
in the Earth's crust.
We take reference environments
from \citet[Table~11.1-11.7]{Valero_2015}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Mixture ($m$)}
\label{sec:exergy_of_mixtures}
%..............................

The total material exergy of a mixture ($B_m$) at a statepoint is

\begin{equation}\label{eq:exergy_mixture}
   B_m = N_m b_m \; ,
 \end{equation}
%
where $B_m$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_m}$,
$N_m$ is the amount of the mixture (in units of $\mathrm{mol_m}$),
and $b_m$ is the molar intensive material exergy of the mixture (in units of $\mathrm{kJ_m/mol_m}$).

The material exergy of a mixture may be account for each species with

\begin{equation}\label{eq:total_exergy_mixture}
   B_m = \sum_i{{N_i}{b_i}}
       = N_m\sum_i{{y_i}{b_i}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $N_i$ ($\mathrm{mol_i}$) is the number of moles of a compound
$b_i$ is the molar intensive material exergy
of a compound ($\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$),
and $y_i$ is the mole fraction
of a compound in a mixture ($\mathrm{mol_i/mol_m}$).


%..............................
\paragraph{Compound ($i$)}
\label{sec:exergy_of_compounds}
%..............................

Molar intensive material exergy ($b_i$) is defined as

\begin{equation}\label{eq:general_material_exergy_definition}
  b_i = b_{ch,i} + b_{c,i} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ch,i}$ is the chemical exergy of a compound (in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$)
and $b_{c,i}$ is the concentration exergy of a compound (in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$).
See \citet[p.~276]{Valero_2015}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Chemical exergy($b_{ch}$)}
\label{ssec:chemical_exergy}
%..............................

% The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$) is the minimum work needed
% to form that compound.
%
% The chemical potential of a species is equal
% in the reference environment and statepoint.
The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$)
that exist in the reference environment
is the potential amount of work obtainable
by decomposing the compound
to compounds and elements
in their environmental stable forms.

If the compound ($i$) does not exist
in the reference environment,
then the chemical exergy is the amount of work obtained
in the reversible chemical reactions
that decompose the pure compound
to the set of compounds
in equilibrium with the environment.
This process can be decomposed into two steps:
(1) decomposition of the compound into elements in their standard states and
(2) conversion of the elements in their environmental stable forms.
The reversible work that is done on the environment associated
with the first process is the Gibbs energy of formation
while the reversible works that are done on the environment associated
with second step are the chemical exergies of those elements.

The chemical exergy of a compound ($b_{ch,i}$) is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:chemical_exergy_definition}
  b_{ch,i} = \Delta{G_{f,i}} + \sum_{i}{n_{j}b_{ch,j}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $b_{ch,i}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$
and Gibbs energy of formation ($\Delta{G_f}$) is in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$.

$\Delta{G_{f}}$ values are taken from \citet[p.9.4-9.94]{Dean_1979}
and \citep[Table~2]{Gibbs_formation}.


%..............................
\paragraph{Concentration Exergy ($b_c$)}
\label{sssec:concentration_exergy}
%..............................

The concentration exergy of a mixture ($b_{c,m}$) is the the minimum work required
to separate the mixture into pure compounds.

The definition of concentration exergy is derived from the entropy of mixing.
The entropy of a mixture ($\Delta{S_m}$) is the increase in entropy
that occurs when different substances are mixed reversibly and isothermally.
The entropy of a mixture ($\Delta{S_m}$) is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:specific_entropy_of_mixture_definition}
  \Delta{S_m} = -RN_m(y_{1}\ln{y_{1}} + y_{2}\ln{y_{2}} + y_{3}\ln{y_{3}} + \ldots)
          = -RN_m\sum_{i} y_{i}\ln{y_{i}} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\Delta{S_m}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol_m \cdot K}$
and $R$ is the universal gas constant (in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol \cdot K}$).

The molar fraction of a species refers back to the species
as a pure substance.
The molar fraction of a pure substance ($y_{i,0}$) is equal to one
because the number of total moles in a mixture
is equivalent to the total moles of the species.
The minimum work required to separate a mixture reversibly
at constant temperature and pressure is given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:work}
    W_{min} = -T_0\Delta{S_m}
            = RT_0 N_m \sum_{i}(y_i\ln{y_i}) \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $W_{min}$ is in units of $\mathrm{kJ/mol_m}$.
The work term is negative
because the environment puts work
into the mixture.

The concentration exergy of a compound (as defined above)
is the reversible work needed to concentrate it to the pure state.
\citet{Valero_2015} define concentration exergy of a compound ($b_{c,i}$) as

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy}
  b_{c,i} = RT_0[\ln(y_i) - \ln(y_{i,0})] \; .
\end{equation}
%

Simplifying Equation (\ref{eq:concentration_exergy})
with $y_{i,0} = 1$ gives

\begin{equation}\label{eq:concentration_exergy_definition}
  b_{c,i} = R T_0 \ln(y_i) \, .
\end{equation}
%
Concentration exergy is always negative
because the pure substance
in the reference environment
becomes less concentrated
at any statepoint.


%..............................
\paragraph{Elements ($j$)}
\label{sssec:elements}
%..............................

The chemical exergy of elements ($b_{ch,j}$) is standardized
based on the Crepuscular Earth Model
from \citet[Table~9.1]{Valero_2015}.
The authors also created a website
that has chemical exergy values \citet{Valero_2018}

The moles of an element within a compound ($n_{j,i}$),
when multiplied by the chemical exergy of the element ($b_{ch,j}$),
is added to the Gibbs free energy ($\Delta{G_f}$)
in \ref{eq:chemical_exergy_definition}.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{The exergy of energy}
\label{sec:exergy_of_energy}
%------------------------------

% Tania: I think we should do it as before -  we should estimate exergy of energy as we did for materials whenever this is possible. When it is not (gibbs energy of formation not available) - we should do it like this.
A material conversion chain
uses both material and energy inputs.
To change a mixture's composition,
energy is used
to concentrate and remove components.

Energy inputs we treat as materials
when the Gibbs energy of formation
is available.
If the Gibbs energy of formation is not available,
then the exergy of energy is calculated by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_definition}
  X_i = \phi_i E_i \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where $\phi_i$ is the exergy to energy ratio and
$E_i$ is the lower heating value of a compound multiplied
by the mass (in units of kJ),
e.g.\ natural gas.

The total exergy of energy
at any statepoint
in a material conversion chain
is given by

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy_exergy_definition}
  X = \sum_i \phi_i E_i \; .
\end{equation}
%
We obtain $\phi$ values from \citet[Appendix~C]{Kotas_1995}.
See Appendix~\ref{sec:appendix_phi}.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{PSUT framework and $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices}
\label{sec:psut_framework}
%------------------------------

The native data format for the CL-PFU database~\citep{Brockway:2024ab} is
the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the
Physical Supply-Use Table (PSUT) framework~\citep{Heun:2018,Aramendia_2022}.
To date, the PSUT framework has been applied
to energy conversion chains~\cite{Heun:2019aa,Aramendia:2024ac};
this paper represents its first application
to unified material and energy conversion chain analysis.

One benefit of the PSUT framework
is that it provides natural structure for data in
material ($M$ in mass units),
energy ($E$ in energy units), and
exergy ($B$ for material and $X$ for energy in exergy units)
conversion chains
developed in Section~\ref{sec:results}
below.
The four matrices of the PSUT framework are
the resource matrix ($\mat{R}$) which contains exogeneous inputs to a conversion chain,
the use ($\mat{U}$) and make ($\mat{V}$) matrices which
describe the consumption and production of materials and energy
by processes in conversion chains, and
the final demand matrix ($\mat{Y}$) which describes consumption
of materials and energy by economic sectors.
(See \citet[Figure~1]{Aramendia_2022}.)


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Material and energy conversion chains}
\label{sec:conversion_chains}
%------------------------------

To illustrate application of the exergy of materials
to societal exergy analysis,
we develop several material and energy conversion chains
using the the $\mat{RUVY}$ matrices of the PSUT framework.
First, we develop
two versions of the example material conversion chain:
(a) A mass-only material conversion chain (MCC) that contains
    mass flows from extraction through a blast furnace
    to the Iron and steel industry
    (Section~\ref{sec:material_data})
    and
(b) an exergy version of the MCC (BCC) wherein material exergies
    are calculated according to Section~\ref{sec:exergy_of_materials}.
In addition, we develop two versions of the
energy conversion chain to supply the MCC's energy requirements:
(c) an energy conversion chain (ECC) extracted from the CL-PFU database
    (Section~\ref{sec:energy_data} and~\ref{sec:ecc_for_mcc})
    and
(d) an exergy version of the ECC (XCC), also
    extracted from the CL-PFU database.
Finally, we develop
(e) a unified conversion chain (BXCC) which
    brings the exergy of materials and energy together,
    as described below.
The basis for all material and energy conversion chains is
1000~kg of iron ore.


