\subsubsection{Process efficiencies}
\label{ssec:efficiency_methods}
%------------------------------

**** Change to matrix equations where possible. ****

We illustrate the application of material exergy to
societal exergy analysis with the PSUT framework
by calculating process efficiencies
throughout the unified conversion chain (BXCC).

\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{images/efficiency_methods.pdf}
  \caption{Three efficiency methods used for energy and material exergy conversion chains.
           ***Change figure***}
  \label{fig:efficiencymethods}
\end{figure}

%
We suggest three methods for calculating efficiencies
based on exergy upgrades, focus on a product,
and focus on whole streams. (See Figure 2.)

\begin{itemize}
  \item The ***Bejan*** method expresses
  how much energy is necessary
  to concentrate a specific element or compound.
  We define ***Bejan*** efficiency as
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:Bejan Efficiency}
    \eta_{Bejan} = \frac{N_i(b_{m,i,1} - b_{m,i,0})}{\sum{X_{in}}} \; .
  \end{equation}
  where $b_{m,i,1}$ is the exergy of a compound in a mixture at statepoint 1 (in units of $\mathrm{kJ_i/mol_i}$)
  and $X_{in}$ is the exergy of all fuel streams, including electricity (in units of $\mathrm{kJ}$).
  \item The ***Resource*** method focuses on the main product stream's exergy output
  compared to the total exergy input.
  The ***Resource*** efficiency is
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:Resource Efficiency}
    \eta_{Resource} = \frac{(B_{m,i,1})}{\sum{X_{in}}+\sum{B_{in}}} \; ,
  \end{equation}
  from \citet[eq.~2.44][p.~32]{Dincer_2007}.
  The ***Resource*** method quantifies
  how efficiently a process
  can produce the desired output.

  \item The ***Rational efficiency*** method focuses on the total exergy output
  compared to the total exergy input.
  \citet[eq.~2.45][p.~32]{Dincer_2007} define ***Rational efficiency*** efficiency as
  \begin{equation}\label{eq:Rational efficiency}
    \eta_{Rational} = \frac{\sum{B_{out}}}{\sum{X_{in}} + \sum{B_{in}}} \; .
  \end{equation}

  The ***Rational efficiency*** method is helpful
  for quick efficiency calculations
  of an overall process.

\end{itemize}

For our purpose, the previous efficiencies
apply to one process
in a material conversion chain.
Larger scale efficiencies
are given by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:Task efficiency}
  \eta_{Task} = \frac{\sum{B_{in,min,theoretical}}}{\sum{B_{in,actual}}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
See \citet[Equation~2.46, p.~32]{Dincer_2007}.



